The Kwara State Command of the Nigeria Security and Civil Defence Corps, NSCDC, has averted a bloody ethnic fight between Hausa and Yoruba at the popular Mandate Market in Ilorin. It was gathered that there was palpable tension when an Hausa man allegedly stabbed a Yoruba man in the head and mouth as the two argued over sales of sugarcane. According to a statement signed by the spokesman of the Nigeria Security and Civil Defence Corps, NSCDC in the State Babawale Zaid Afolabi, it took the timely arrival of the NSCDC operatives and other security personnel to prevent what could have resulted into a bloody ethnic clash. Uzodimma Has Refused To Name Sponsors Of Insecurity –… NAF Appoints New Branch Chiefs, Air Officers Commanding, Other… He said, “We got a distress call on Tuesday that there was a clash between Yoruba and Hausa at Mandate market and we quickly mobilized our men to the scene in order to prevent total breakdown of law and other.” According to reports,trouble started when a Yoruba man reportedly bought a sugarcane worth N50 naira from one Hausa seller but found out that the sugarcane was not sweet. The Yoruba man’s request to change the sugarcane did not go down well with the Hausa man. The Hausa man however allegedly stabbed the Yoruba man and this resulted in a free-for-all between Hausa and Yoruba inside the market. “The NSCDC Commandant in the state ,Iskilu Ayinla Makinde, has ordered 24 hours surveillance and presence of our armed plain cloth personnel around the market premises and all the flash points have also been identified and necessary actions have been taken,” the spokesman added.